Layer-1

ZK Compression: Rollups, Stateless Client, or a Secret Third Thing?
Kunal Goel
Seth Bloomberg

a day ago ⋅  7 min read

Primer

Two of the largest constraints on blockchain systems are the costs associated with computation and state management.

Every onchain transaction (e.g., token swaps, NFT mints, contract deployment, etc) has to be validated and executed by nodes on the network. The cost of this computation varies from network to network. On one extreme is Ethereum mainnet, where a simple token swap currently costs ~$10; alternatively, transactions on Solana are usually well under a fraction of a cent.

State management typically refers to managing the impact of a blockchain's ever-growing state. As new users are onboarded onto a network via collecting NFTs, buying/selling tokens, or deploying new contracts and applications, the state of a blockchain grows. Broadly speaking, there is not necessarily an upper bound on the size of the state since its growth is a direct consequence of and driven by the activity and growth of the network itself. Solana, for example, explicitly charges users for this cost via a rental fee.

As noted above, Solana is largely unconstrained by computation costs due to its low transaction fees. However, the costs associated with state are still relatively expensive. To address the high costs associated with Solana state, Helius and Light protocol introduced ZK compression.

At a high level, Solana’s ZK compression allows a large set of accounts (e.g., user addresses and a specific token balance) to be securely represented onchain by a relatively small identifier. This compression technique leads to dramatically reduced state costs.

The ZK compression system leverages a Merkle tree structure, a data structure commonly used in a blockchain context. To demonstrate the mechanics of ZK compression, consider a set of users and their token balances.

The lowest level of the Merkle tree structure (known as leaves) represents the set of users and their individual token balances. Each layer above performs a hashing process so that the entirety of the Merkle tree’s data is eventually represented by a single hash (also known as a Merkle root or root hash). The cost savings found with this architecture are due to the fact that only the fixed-sized Merkle root (and a small subset of the tree itself) is posted onchain. The majority of the underlying Merkle tree data (e.g., individual user account balances and the majority of the Merkle tree) is kept in Solana’s ledger storage space.

When a user’s token balance needs to be updated (e.g., when they send tokens to a different account), a ZK (validity) proof is generated that ensures the user’s current balance matches the resultant onchain root hash. Once that is verified, the Solana network runs the computation to update the token balance, and the tree structure is updated.

Since most of the data is held in Solana’s ledger space, which Solana nodes are not required to retain in full, additional offchain infrastructure providers are leveraged when modifications are needed to the tree (e.g., when a user transfers tokens and their balance must be updated). An indexer or RPC node (such as Helius) helps with the ZK proof generation and supplies additional offchain data required for the overall workflow.

While the above example describes ZK compression for token accounts, the big unlock here is that this system can be generalized to all accounts on Solana. This is important, as, technically, all smart contracts are accounts on Solana, which is different than other smart contract platforms such as Ethereum.

In addition, since the execution is occurring on Solana, compressed accounts are technically composable with normal, onchain accounts. This means compressed accounts can interact with normal accounts and their state. Structurally, this is different than Ethereum and its ecosystem of rollups since accounts on rollups are generally not composable with one another.

Analyst Discussion

Seth

The launch of Solana’s ZK compression was accompanied by general intrigue from those interested in understanding the technical underpinnings of the new system, especially in comparison to many features associated with Ethereum. Regardless of how it’s classified, it does give Solana application developers an immediate unlock.

For example, as Mert points out, prior to ZK compression, creating a token and airdropping it to one million users creates a unit cost (assuming a SOL price of $140) of ~$0.28 per account, or ~$260,000 in total state cost. Applying this same scenario but leveraging ZK compression reduces the total state cost to ~$56, a 5000x reduction in cost. This level of cost reduction enables both scaled, offchain businesses to experiment with onchain features (e.g., tokens) or, more broadly, open up new business models to be explored.

Conceptually, this unlock is similar to compressed NFTs' (cNFT) impact on Solana. Teams such as Drip and Helium have taken advantage of the highly reduced cost of cNFT minting. When it migrated to Solana in 2023, Helium, for example, minted ~962,000 cNFTs to 210,000 users, totaling a cost of 4.8 SOL.

However, the current architecture of ZK compression has tradeoffs and limitations. As the Light protocol notes, ZK compression is not intended to be used if the account will be updated within a single block (e.g., a highly used DeFi pool containing high-volume pairs) or if the account will be written to hundreds of thousands of times over the course of its life. For both cases, the cumulative costs of the updates will effectively negate the offchain state cost savings. Additionally, at least in the short term, there will be dependence on indexers to ensure access is readily available to compressed accounts and associated data. Over the longer term, this will likely be a non-issue as there is an open-source indexer implementation, but in the meantime, reliance on a single indexer provider could lead to outages.

In the grander view, this will be a highly leveraged value proposition and general unlock for Solana and its application developers. Instead of intentionally moving users and economies to different execution environments, which fractures liquidity and can degrade UX, Solana retains this activity on its base layer. For application developers, as ZK compression is refined over time, new use cases that have historically not been (economically) feasible will emerge.

Kunal

There has been much discussion over whether Solana’s ZK Compression is a rollup, a validium, a stateless client, or something entirely else. However, the semantic discussion is not nearly as important as the potential impact it has on Solana.

As Seth notes, Solana has very cheap compute and large blocks, which means that its state grows quickly. State growth is an unsolved problem that affects all blockchains but impacts fast blockchains much more as their state grows very quickly. These chains, including Solana, have used “state rent” as a way to limit state growth while a solution is found. ZK Compression is a step forward in this unsolved problem. First, there was a specific implementation of minting compressed NFTs, now it is more generalized to fungible tokens as well. Further generalizing compression will continue to mitigate the problem of state growth.

Additionally, beyond scaling the state, Light Protocol also expects ZK Compression to unlock new applications and use cases through custom ZK compute. Zero-knowledge has the potential for significant unlocks beyond just privacy. The product is in testnet but I expect there will be new applications when it launches.

Finally, ZK Compression is a testament to the relentless developer focus that sets Solana apart. Instead of every update being a multi-year project, Solana improves in weeks. In the week following ZK Compression’s announcement, Solana announced Blinks, a quick way to interact with Solana without leaving Web 2 apps through a browser plugin. This design unlock is still available to all other blockchains, however, I expect there may be some time before we see them implemented on any other blockchain.
